# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1915-philadelphia-phillies-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] The **1915 Philadelphia Phillies season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] It involved the Phillies winning the National League, then going on to lose the World Series to the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] This was the team's first pennant since joining the league in 1883.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] It would have to wait another thirty-five years for its second — and another sixty-five years for its first World Championship.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] The pitching staff allowed the fewest runs in the NL.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] It was led by Hall of Famer Grover Cleveland Alexander, who had one of the greatest seasons in history and won the pitching triple crown.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] Outfielder Gavvy Cravath, aided by the small Baker Bowl park, led the majors in home runs, runs batted in, and slugging percentage.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] The Phillies won 3 to 1, although *The New York Times* reporter Hugh Fullerton wrote, "Alexander pitched a bad game of ball.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] He had little or nothing." He titled his article, "Nothing but luck saved the Phillies." The Times also reported that 10,000 people gathered in New York City's Times Square to watch a real-time mechanical recreation of the game on a giant scoreboard sponsored by the newspaper.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] On October 16, 1915, a testimonial dinner was given to honor the 1915 Phillies for the franchise's first pennant.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] The dinner took place at The Bellevue-Stratford Hotel.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] Speakers included Philadelphia mayor Rudolph Blankenburg, Phillies owner William Baker, National League president John Tener, and Phillies manager Pat Moran.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] The team marked its 25th anniversary in 1940 when the pennant remained the club's lone to date.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] Gerry Nugent announced in April 1940 that the organization would welcome back the players from the 1915 team to celebrate the anniversary.
[src:1915-philadelphia-phillies-season/1915-philadelphia-phillies-season] Bill Killefer, Bert Neihoff, Milt Stock, and Ben Tincup all remained in organized baseball in 1940 as managers or coaches.
